The Catacombs of Nightfall lie beneath the southern chapel quarter of Midgaard, accessible from the civic core through the Ossuary Transport Court.
They began as a sanctioned burial-adjudication complex during the Lantern era: processing the dead, settling debts, and archiving oaths.
During the Violet Compact era, the same registry that documented arcane materials entering the Gloamvault also catalogued remains entering Nightfall.
The same sealed warrants authorizing prisoner transfers to the Dungeon also authorized reclassification of unclaimed bodies as civic remainder.
Two incompatible worldviews were embedded from founding: Midgaard's bureaucratic doctrine that order is memory made legible, and forest oath doctrine that memory must remain in living cycle.
The catacombs sit at the intersection of the Violet Reliquary Arch and the Dungeon Intake Yard — proximity that was not accidental.
The long trajectory of Nightfall is the conversion of institutional partnership to institutional predation.
Forest oath materials — memory relics, root-oath tablets, and living-soil burial requests — were catalogued under civic remainder classifications and reclassified for archive use.
The Nightfall registry became one of the largest secondary archives for oaths that should have remained in forest circulation.
Oath-wraiths and ledger-bound undead now populate the deeper tiers, enforcing administrative procedures that outlived their legal authority.
The catacombs are not a cult dungeon but a bureaucratic ruin: a place where lawful record-keeping became extractive possession.

