From Umbral perspective, the Catacombs of Nightfall are remarkable for what is absent: the shadow-record of what was reclassified rather than what was preserved.
Umbral assessment distinguishes between deliberate concealment and procedural erasure; Nightfall represents the latter — records not hidden but overwritten, creating a shadow-archive of displaced content.
The deeper tiers contain shadow-impressions of forest oath materials processed through civic remainder classification: not the oaths themselves, but the shapes left in the institutional record by their absence.
Umbral-sensitive observers report a deeper layer of impression-entities — the administrative record of the reclassification itself, still performing its institutional function in the shadow layer.
Umbral navigation within the catacombs is complicated by the density of crossed shadow-records: civic registry impressions overlaying forest oath shadows, creating interference patterns that disrupt standard shadow-movement.
The Nightfall shadow layer is considered one of the densest institutional-shadow sites near Midgaard, more complex than the Gloamvault because the reclassification accumulated through procedural momentum rather than intentional design.

flags MIDGAARD USHABTI
---
Ushabti cosmic law assessment of the Catacombs of Nightfall centers on jurisdictional illegitimacy: the Violet Compact's civic remainder classification applied administrative authority to materials whose legal status was already settled under prior oath law.
Cosmic law recognizes oath obligations as binding regardless of subsequent institutional reclassification; a forest oath filed as civic remainder remains legally active under cosmic jurisprudence even if void under Midgaard's civil code.
This creates a dual-jurisdiction condition Ushabti legal scholars describe as an unresolved cosmic docket: cases that are administratively closed but cosmically open.
The oath-wraith population enforces cosmic docket obligations — they are active jurisdictional agents operating under pre-civic legal authority that was never properly superseded.
Defeating or dispersing oath-wraiths without resolving the underlying docket is a cosmic law violation: it destroys jurisdictional agents without closing the cases they are enforcing.
Proper resolution would require either cosmic law closure (voiding the original oaths through recognized oath-dissolution procedure) or civic law correction (restoring reclassified materials to proper legal status). Neither has been pursued because both require acknowledging the original reclassification's illegitimacy under cosmic law standards.
